---
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import Quote from '../../components/Quote.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'judge-and-witnesses')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    At the foot of every shield chart stand three figures that sum up the whole: the
    <em>Right Witness</em> (made from the first and second Nieces), the <em>Left Witness</em>
    (from the third and fourth), and the <em>Judge</em>, made from the two Witnesses together.
    The Judge delivers the general sentence of the question (good or evil) before any house is
    examined; the Witnesses show the parties, the beginning and the end of the matter.
  </p>
  <p>
    Because of the way it is generated, the Judge always has an even number of points: an odd
    Judge means a miscast chart. Agrippa calls the Witnesses <em>Coadjutrices</em> or
    <em>Testes</em>, and the figure made from them the index of the whole figure:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="judge-witnesses" />
  <p>
    Crowley's <em>Handbook</em> preserves a complete set of tables (omitted from Regardie's
    Golden Dawn papers) giving the verdict of every combination of Witnesses and Judge for ten
    standard matters (life, money, rank, property, marriage, children, sickness, prison, journeys
    and things lost): see <a href="/library/crowley/witnesses-and-judge/">the Tables of Witnesses
    and Judge</a> in the library.
  </p>
</Prose>
